all research and development activity—from planning through execution—DTIC is undergoing a pivotal transformation. By expanding its vast collections and integrating
with advanced artificial intelligence and machine learning models, DTIC is evolving into a proactive tool for strategic foresight. This in turn will empower the Department
with collective awareness, horizon scanning, and trend analysis, enabling DoW researchers to avoid duplication, deploy resources more efficiently and effectively,
and deliver enhanced capabilities to our warfighters faster. The transformation of DTIC’s infrastructure and platform in support of an AI-enabled repository is a critical
investment, designed to accelerate our technical maturity and secure decision advantage for senior leaders.

 To realize the full potential of its transformation, DTIC must cultivate strong partnerships across the research ecosystem. The vision of leveraging DoW’s strategic
 research assets and artificial intelligence and machine learning capabilities explicitly acknowledges that DTIC cannot achieve its goals in isolation. Strategic
 collaboration with the Joint Staff, military departments, Combatant Commands, Office of the Chief Digital and Artificial Intelligence Officer, OUSW Comptroller, DCAPE,
 DoW CIO, FFRDCs, etc. is paramount. These partnerships provide access to data sources, cutting-edge technologies, and specialized expertise, that are essential for a
 complete collection and rapid integration of AI/ML for sophisticated analysis.$$, $$The Information Analysis Centers (IAC) program provides the essential, centralized capability that rapidly bridges the gap between DoW's sprawling scientific and
technical research enterprise and the urgent need to field state of the art technological capabilities for the warfighter. The core challenge facing the DoW R&D
community is the inability to efficiently locate, synthesize, and reuse technical data across disparate labs and organizations. This decentralized environment creates
significant technical and financial risk, leading to unintentional duplication of effort, slower development cycles, and critical technological gaps.
The IAC program directly mitigates these risks by serving as the primary nexus for technical collaboration. With an existing network of approximately 700 partner
organizations, the IAC is a critical force multiplier that accelerates technology transition and development by performing three core functions:
• Synthesizing Knowledge: Leveraging DTIC's repository to generate technical information analysis and products, enabling reuse and reducing technical risk for new
programs.
• Supporting Applied Research: Utilizing scientific and technical information (STI) to directly support ongoing basic and applied research, ensuring that "lessons learned"
are integrated early in the development lifecycle.
• Facilitating Complex Research: Executing primary research directly or jointly to solve interagency challenges where seamless STI sharing is a prerequisite.

 By centralizing and streamlining access to innovation, IAC provides a decisive strategic advantage, enabling program managers and developers to build upon a
 foundation of existing knowledge rather than starting from scratch.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                        FY 2025           FY 2026       FY 2027
Title: Information Analysis Centers                                                                                                            5.016             5.016         5.016
Description: In FY 2025, IAC demonstrated the immense value of this model by fulfilling 4,900 direct technical inquiries and
producing 183 detailed technical products, creating an exponential return on investment. Furthermore, the program facilitated 42
high-impact SME training events, directly upskilling the DoW workforce in emerging domains.

This operational success fueled significant program growth and momentum:
• Portfolio Growth: The demand for IAC's core services escalated exponentially, supporting a joint R&D portfolio exceeding $3.5
Billion—demonstrating profound customer validation from across the Defense enterprise.
• Knowledge Base Expansion: The program's commitment to "continuously reusable innovation" successfully onboarded 9,000
new research documents to the DTIC repository, ensuring future R&D efforts have a richer foundation.
• Mission Partner Expansion: In FY 2025, IAC expanded its reach by onboarding 65 new DoW organizations as mission partners.

                                                                                ation Center

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2025      FY 2026      FY 2027
• Targeted Innovation: IAC directly prioritized and accelerated technology integration within the Critical Technology Areas (CTA),
including pivotal advancements in Microelectronics, Hypersonics, Directed Energy, Cyber, Autonomy, and Artificial Intelligence/
Machine Learning (AI/ML).

FY 2026 Plans:
Funding is critical to scale IAC's impact and leverage emerging technology to increase internal efficiency. Specific plans include:
• Scalable Capability Delivery: Maintaining continuous research, analysis, and transition services to the entire DoW research
community, utilizing the robust $48 Billion Information Analysis Centers Multiple Award Contract (IACMAC) vehicle to increase the
speed of R&D task order awards.
• Technological Modernization: Capitalizing on current AI/ML advancements to transform internal process management. This
includes applying AI/ML to automate funding document processing, streamline performance work statement development, and
optimize deliverable tracking and analysis. This targeted investment will reduce operational overhead, control contractor support
costs, and accelerate the "speed of contract" to meet emergent needs.
• Strategic Expansion: Continuing to highlight and grow research and analysis services within DoW laboratories focused on Basic
Research, ensuring foundational innovation is properly postured for rapid transition to applied programs.
• Domain Focus: Maintaining a dedicated technical focus across three critical and evolving domains: Cyber Security, Defense
Systems, and Homeland Defense.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Execute IACMAC Follow-On Award: Finalize and award the competitive follow-on contract vehicle to the current $48B
Information Analysis Center Multiple Award Contract (IACMAC). This effort is critical to ensuring zero-gap in R&D contracting
support for the DoW S&T community. The follow-on will continue to provide a streamlined, best-value acquisition platform for
RDT&E services across the 22 Technical Focus Areas (TFAs).
• Transition and Onboarding: Initiate a robust transition plan to migrate existing mission partners and requirements to the new
contract vehicle. This includes conducting post-award orientations for new industry partners (Pools 1, 2, and 3) to ensure
immediate operational readiness and compliance with the latest DoW acquisition and cybersecurity standards.
• Critical Technology Support: Expand targeted research and analysis support for the Under Secretary of Defense for Research
and Engineering (USW(R&E)) in top-tier Critical Technology Areas. Focus will be placed on accelerating the transition of
Microelectronics, Hypersonics, and AI/ML prototypes from the laboratory to the Warfighter through the new contract’s agile task
order structure.
• Operationalize AI/ML Management Tools: Fully deploy the AI/ML-driven process efficiencies. This includes using automated
tools for rapid Performance Work Statement (PWS) development and enhanced deliverable analysis, reducing the average
procurement administrative lead time (PALT) for complex R&D requirements.

                                                                               ation Center

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2025     FY 2026        FY 2027
• Enhance Knowledge Reuse: Systematize the ingestion of Scientific and Technical Information (STI) from the new contract’s first-
year task orders into the DTIC repository. This ensures that the 9,000+ yearly research documents continue to feed a “loop of
continuous capability development,” preventing R&D duplication across the Department.
• Expand SME Network Engagement: Increase the frequency and technical depth of SME training events and technical inquiries.
