INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0604657M$$, 2027, $$The Organic Precision Fires (OPF) program supports the Commandant of the Marine Corps' (CMC) Force Design initiative, and is in direct response to the Secretary of
War's mandate for a more lethal and distributed Joint Force. This program equips multiple levels of command within the Fleet Marine Force with an organic, loitering,
and precise "over-the-horizon" strike capability, fundamentally changing the tactical equation at all levels from the squad to the battalion.

By placing this capability directly into the hands of our infantry and reconnaissance Marines, OPF empowers them to engage the enemy immediately upon detection,
well beyond the range of their direct-fire weapons. This increases the lethality while simultaneously enhancing the survivability by minimizing exposure to enemy fire.

Extensive war-gaming, simulation, and real-world operational experience have validated that OPF is not merely an incremental improvement; it is a transformational
leap in combat effectiveness. It provides the small-unit leader with the tools to create dilemmas for our adversaries, hold key maritime terrain, and thrive in complex,
distributed environments where traditional fire support may be unavailable or too slow to respond. This program is essential to building the agile, highly lethal force
required to win in the contested battlefields of the future.$$, $$Organic Precision Fires (OPF) is a Marine Corps modernization priority and will provide multiple echelons of the Fleet Marine Force with an organic, loitering, beyond-
line-of-sight precision strike capability. OPF will deliver precision effects as well as surveillance before and during target strike, while reducing the potential for collateral
damage. Multiple materiel solutions are required to provide the envisioned capabilities to the Fleet Marine Force.

OPF-Light (OPF-L) procures an existing light-weight loitering munition system for use by dismounted elements. It provides a dismounted, lightweight, man-packable,
loitering munition that extends the capability of the infantry squad/platoon to engage targets to the maximum range of organic Intelligence, Surveillance, and
Reconnaissance (ISR) assets at that level. OPF-L will provide a counter-defilade, anti-personnel and anti-materiel capability. Primary target sets for this system will be
enemy personnel, crew-served weapons, and Command and Control (C2) nodes. This will be principally a platoon/squad level asset.

OPF-Medium (OPF-M) will procure an existing dismounted anti-armor/anti-personnel loitering munition system capable of being launched from the ground. Primary
target sets for this system will be armored targets, dismounted personnel, and fortified emplacements/structures. This will be principally a company/platoon level asset.

In FY 2026, OPF-L completed DT2, conducted operational testing, and began development and testing of OPF-L capability enhancements which will provide greater
lethality effects over the base capability including upgrades for target recognition and warhead performance. In FY 2027, OPF-L will continue development and testing
of capability enhancements for target recognition and initiate enhancements for navigation and operations in a contested environment. In addition, the Marine Corps will
initiate OPF-M, a new capability with a separate materiel solution from OPF-L. OPF-M will procure an existing, man-portable loitering munition for use by dismounted
elements to engage targets at a significantly greater range, increased loiter time and increased lethality, to include an anti-armor capability.

