Title: Exponentiating Mathematics (expMath)                                                                                              -       13.899        14.131
Description: The Exponentiating Mathematics (expMath) program is developing and applying artificial intelligence (AI) techniques
to enable breakthrough advances in national security-related mathematical fields. At present, important problems in mathematics
take decades or centuries to resolve, but recent advances in generative AI (genAI) and large language models (LLMs) offer
the promise of accelerating advances in mathematics. expMath aims to use AI to automate the discovery of new mathematical
knowledge. Creating an AI with these mathematical capabilities will require advances along two fronts: decomposition/abstraction
and formalization/informalization. expMath focuses on mathematical domains of particular importance for national security. If
successful, expMath will provide the basis for potential leap-ahead mathematical capabilities for the U.S.

Prior to FY 2026, this program was funded in PE 0601101E, Project CCS-02.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Develop automated techniques for translating natural language lemmas into formal language, executing proof steps when
possible, and translating the derived proof back to natural language.
- Formulate mathematical problems in domains relevant to national security in terms amenable to automated analysis by an AI
system specialized to discover mathematical knowledge.
- Explore architectural implementation options for an AI system specialized to perform the decomposition/abstraction and
formalization/informalization functions required for the discovery of mathematical knowledge.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Integrate automated mathematical techniques in an AI system capable of performing complex mathematical derivations and
proofs.
- Perform initial demonstrations of mathematical knowledge discovery on mathematical problem domains/sub-domains of
particular importance for national security.
- Demonstrate math automation capabilities at a major mathematics and/or AI conference and to U.S. Government and
Department of War stakeholders.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:




