Title: Mapping Machine Learning to Physics (ML2P)                                                                                            -        4.411         2.789
Description: The Mapping Machine Learning to Physics (ML2P) program aims to develop energy-aware machine learning
(ML) technology to enable the military to adapt ML on the battlefield under conditions of limited power resources. The capability
to adapt ML systems in the field will be important for the military to keep ML systems up-to-date and current with evolving
threats. ML2P will map ML efficiency to physics by using precise granular measurements in joules and metrics that are directly
comparable across hardware architectures. ML2P will construct energy-aware ML optimized for power and performance for a
given task and candidate hardware for the life cycle of the model. ML2P will develop objective functions that are optimal, feasible,
and provide the desired trade-off for power and performance for a diversity of objective functions and applications. ML2P will
discover the power-performance interactions between local optimizations and facilitate energy-aware ML construction and
optimization. Success in the ML2P program will enable the military to create ML systems that can be sustained under conditions of
limited power resources such as are likely to be encountered in battlefield environments.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Map machine learning (ML) energy efficiency to physics using precise granular measurements in joules and metrics that are
directly comparable across hardware architectures.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Construct energy-aware ML and evaluate power usage and performance for a given task.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
The FY 2027 decrease reflects a shift from development to evaluation of energy-efficient ML models.
Title: Advanced Tools for Modeling and Simulation                                                                                            -        6.771         1.751
Description: The Advanced Tools for Modeling and Simulation thrust is developing foundational mathematical, computational,
and multi-physics theories, approaches, and tools to better represent, quantify, and model complex Department of War (DoW)
systems from multimodal data analysis through part/system design and fabrication. One focus area of this thrust is developing a
unified mathematical framework to enable better visualization and analysis of massive, complex data sets. Rigorous mathematical

