Title: Next Generation Electronic Surveillance Technology (NGEST)                                                                             -        7.389         6.911
Description: The Next Generation Electronic Surveillance Technology (NGEST) program is creating a new Radio Frequency (RF)
surveillance system for sensing in complex signal environments. NGEST is defining a new surveillance paradigm to find critical
signals of interest in tactically relevant timelines. Contemporary electronic surveillance systems face increasing RF complexity
in the spatial (emitter proliferation), power (range), and frequency (agility, congestion) dimensions due to their static hardware
configuration. Additionally, current systems need to employ exquisite hardware to deal with geometrical challenges. NGEST
overcomes the complexity and geometry challenges by autonomously reconfiguring diverse frequency and spatial resources.

Prior to FY 2026, this program was funded in PE 0602702E, Project TT-07.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Integrate hardware components of prototype RF surveillance system.
- Integrate orchestration algorithms into prototype RF surveillance system and test in a laboratory environment.
- Field test initial prototype system in a complex signal environment.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Conduct additional field and laboratory testing in complex signal environments.
- Upgrade system prototype based on lessons learned from field and laboratory testing.
- Finalize system design and open architecture interfaces.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
The FY 2027 decrease reflects a shift from system integration to final testing.
Title: All Domain Tactical Technologies Studies and Concepts                                                                                  -        8.786        33.547
Description: The All Domain Tactical Technologies Concepts and Studies will investigate system concepts for developing
technologies to enhance U.S. military effectiveness and survivability in operations across all domains. Efforts will surmount
key challenges associated with redefining access and timely delivery of effects by using targeted investments that explore the
feasibility of novel technical solutions, force capabilities, and innovations in logistics and manufacturing. These may include
feasibility studies of novel or emergent materials; sensors, effectors, and tactics for air, space, ground, and sea platforms; launch
vehicles; satellites; manufacturing and implementation approaches; and hardware demonstrations of key enabling technologies.


