Title: eX Virentia (eXVi)                                                                                                                  -       12.487        12.839
Description: The eX Virentia (eXVi) program is investigating the use of existing unmodified vegetation as a sensor to identify
activities of DoW interest by utilizing natural plant responses to man-made chemical exposures. The eXVi program will bring
together the research communities of plant biology, remote sensing, and computational modeling to uncover the internal
biochemical response of plant species to chemical exposure, and how they relate to external observable characteristics. The
program will grow plant species across various types of vegetation, measure internal and external responses, and model
the responses with the goal of scaling predicted responses to similar species across phylogenies. If successful, discovery of
predictable and distinct cause-and-effect relationships between exposure and plant response will significantly improve situational
awareness of hazards and materials activity, thereby limiting harmful exposure to the warfighter.

Prior to FY 2026, this program was funded in PE 0602715E, Project MBT-02.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Initiate plant acquisition, growth, and stabilization for selected species.
- Initiate plant chemical exposure experiments to identify biochemical, molecular, and physiological patterns associated with
exposure of plants to target stressors.
- Perform plant exposure evaluations using multi-omics and external observable measurements.
- Develop plant biological process model(s) to understand biochemical, molecular, and physiological patterns associated with
exposure of plants to selected stressors.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Complete long term plant growth and stabilization for selected species to support scaling approach.
- Complete chemical exposure experiments to identify biochemical, molecular, and physiological patterns associated with
exposure of plants to target stressors.
- Evaluate plant exposure using multi-omics and external observable measurements.
- Determine whether external plant observables provide a distinct, predictable, and scalable indicator of chemical exposure.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:

