Title: Heterogeneous Architectures for Quantum (HARQ)                                                                                      -       14.500        15.000
Description: The Heterogeneous Architectures for Quantum (HARQ) program aims to demonstrate the scaling advantages of
heterogeneous architectures for quantum computers. Large-scale quantum computers have long been lauded as a potentially
revolutionary capability. While the race to build a quantum computer is drawing substantial attention and investment, all on-
going work is focused on homogeneous architectures that essentially place a bet on a single qubit modality. Unfortunately, this
handicaps any such future machine's ultimate scale and accessible computation space due to the inability for any single qubit
platform to optimally perform all necessary functions for quantum computation. Heterogeneous architectures may offer a path to
scale systems beyond present-day industry roadmaps and enable transformative commercial and national security opportunities,
such as the discovery of superior anti-corrosion coatings for defense platforms, energetics for propulsion, and pharmaceutical
drug delivery. HARQ seeks to create a modeling and simulation framework that determines the computational efficiency
enhancement afforded by the ability to allocate the execution of quantum applications to diverse qubit technologies. Additionally,
HARQ will drive the development of hardware components that rapidly and efficiently transfer quantum states between diverse
qubit technologies, which will be necessary to interface between disparate qubit modules in a future heterogeneous architecture.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Develop initial designs for components of heterogeneous quantum interconnects.
- Develop initial modeling & simulation frameworks for partitioning quantum circuits in heterogeneous architecture.
- Establish an independent verification and validation capable of performing technoeconomic analysis on heterogeneous quantum
computer architecture.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Demonstrate initial components of heterogeneous quantum interconnects.
- Demonstrate heterogeneous quantum circuit compilers on small reference circuits.



