of money laundering largely via manual searches of a myriad of commercial and financial intelligence (FININT) databases and
rule-based AML systems that lack flexibility to adapt to changing TTPs. Because of the static nature of current AML processes
and the limited capabilities of AML tools, novel money laundering schemes can go on for years. To address this challenge,
A3ML will develop and apply graph search and subgraph isomorphism techniques that reference high-level models of money
laundering to extract specific money laundering TTPs from heterogeneous transaction data and to anticipate and adapt to new
money laundering TTPs in a timely fashion. If successful, A3ML technologies and tools would enhance AML practices across U.S.
Government (USG) and the private sector.

Beginning in FY 2026, this program will be funded in PE 0602025E, Project MSL-05.

Title: Artificial Intelligence Quantified (AIQ)                                                                                                   8.000             -            -
Description: The Artificial Intelligence Quantified (AIQ) program is developing technologies for assessing the capabilities of
generative artificial intelligence (genAI) to enable mathematical guarantees on performance. Current state-of-the-art methods
for genAI quantification and assessment are ad hoc, deal with only the simplest of capabilities, and are not properly grounded in
a rigorous theory. The AIQ approach combines mathematical methods with advances in measurement and modeling to enable
rigorous quantification of genAI capabilities. The program addresses three capability levels: 1) the specific problem level, which
addresses quantification for a given problem; 2) the classes of problem level, which address quantification of a given problem
class; and 3) the natural class level which addresses the reverse question of the class of problems quantifiable for a given genAI
architecture. Success with AIQ will provide guarantees on the performance of genAI technologies.

Beginning in FY 2026, this program will be funded in PE 0602025E, Project MSL-05.

Title: Kallisti                                                                                                                                   6.000             -            -
Description: The Kallisti program seeks to develop new capabilities for modeling adversarial behaviors. Actions taken by
independent state and non-state actors are determined by their beliefs about the state of their environment, the risks and rewards
associated with these beliefs, and the strategy they use to react to the risks or rewards they believe exist in their environment.
This program is developing an algorithmic model of behaviors by independent actors through inferring and understanding the
belief states that might deter or result in distribution of actions. Kallisti's modeling will allow projection of an actor's future behavior
based on their perceived strategy, enabling external actions to be taken. The program seeks not only to understand an actor's
current strategy but also to find a decomposed version of the strategy into relevant basis vectors to track strategy changes under
non-stationary assumptions. The primary goal is to utilize algorithmic modeling of beliefs and behaviors to deter aggression by
military adversaries. Technology developed under this program will transition to the Services.



