B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                    FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027
Title: Bio-Inspired Coastal Defense                                                                                                       13.721          -             -
Description: The Bio-Inspired Coastal Defense program developed self-sustaining, hybrid man-made and biological reef
structures to fortify and defend DoW bases in low-lying coastal regions. Military assets in these coastal regions face storm-driven
wave action that causes erosion, degrades infrastructure, and impedes operations. Innovative coastal defense requires major
technological advances in (1) design, construction, and placement of manufactured reef primers; (2) accelerated recruitment and/
or growth of reef species; and (3) sustained, zero-cost natural maintenance and improvement (e.g., increased durability after
anchor and materials testing) of the defensive reef. The primary benefit of such structures is to attenuate wave height during storm
events for both established and under construction coastal facilities.

Title: Signal Processing and Communication with Biotechnology                                                                            10.964              -            -
Description: The DoW requires the ability to monitor complex operating domains with sufficient resolution and confidence to
inform missions and protect personnel and platforms against various physical and chemical threats. The Signal Processing
and Communication with Biotechnology program developed a new customizable sensing methodology using a novel microbe-
based, platform technology capable of detecting a variety of input signals, processing information, and generating multiple output
signal types in diverse operational conditions. Technology developed in this program will offer insight into signal processing and
transmission methodologies with logistical advantages and reliable operability in contested domains.

Title: Bioremediation of Battlefields                                                                                                      2.325             -            -
Description: The Bioremediation of Battlefields program addressed the DoW need to stabilize and remediate sites impacted by
prior military activities, including contaminated combat zones, defense installations, and test ranges. This research supported
the safety of service members and local communities and minimized the impact of warfare by developing biological tools that
remediate soil contamination. This program's aim was to eliminate contaminants, and thus restore habitability, by identifying and
optimizing organisms, such as microbes, fungi, and plants, that could detect toxic compounds, mitigate their impact, and report
on the state of remediation. Bioremediation of Battlefields demonstrated technologies in the laboratory that could reduce the long-
term impacts of military activities and improve the overall health and land use potential for contaminated sites.

Title: Unburdening the Warfighter from Chemical/Biological (CB) Defense                                                                    1.482             -            -
Description: The Unburdening the Warfighter from Chemical/Biological (CB) Defense program aimed to increase warfighter
survivability by developing improved personal protective equipment (PPE) and medical countermeasure technologies to protect
against CB threats. Current methods of CB protection require significant logistical burdens, including suits that are bulky and hot,
which limit operational effectiveness. These burdens increase if additional levels of protection are required. The Unburdening
the Warfighter from CB Defense program investigated and designed novel biological and material approaches that provide rapid
protection against multiple CB agents for the warfighter. This research innovated PPE through the discovery of compounds

