Title: Highly Accelerated Learnings of Vibratory Systems (HALOVS)                                                                         14.000          -             -
Description: The Highly Accelerated Learning of Vibratory Systems (HALOVS) portfolio investigates the foundational limits and
transformative potential of vibratory sensors for positioning and navigation in GPS-denied environments. By leveraging advances
in 3D micromachining, material science, and dynamic modeling, HALOVS explores novel architectures and principles through
efforts examining ultrafast microsystems, higher-order composite resonators for extra resilience, and chemistries and monolayers
for anti-aging kinematics. These efforts aim to address critical challenges in sensor performance, including operating beyond
linear regimes to achieve high-velocity motion, leveraging nonlinearities for enhanced resilience to shock and vibration, and
extending sensor longevity by addressing drift and aging at the molecular level. The insights and technologies developed within
HALOVS promise to redefine the design space and practical limits of vibratory sensors, delivering capabilities essential to national
security and global positioning system (GPS)-denied missions.

Beginning in FY 2026, this program will be funded in PE 0602025E, Project MSL-03.

Title: Sync                                                                                                                              10.000              -            -
Description: The Sync program is creating systems to defend against uncrewed underwater vehicles (UUVs) entering U.S.
harbors and ports. Today's counter-UUV approaches rely on complex detection and localization methods to find UUVs prior to
engagement. The Sync program looks at orthogonal approaches to solving this problem to defeat UUVs prior to detection. Sync is
investigating several different approaches to defeat UUVs, starting with modeling and simulation eventually moving to hardware in
the loop and pool testing.

Beginning in FY 2026, this program will be funded in PE 0602026E, Project EFF-01.

Title: Microsystem Induced CAtalysis (MICA)                                                                                              15.000              -            -
Description: The Microsystem Induced CAtalysis (MICA) program is developing advanced concepts for microsystem control of
biological function. The program seeks hardware demonstrations of molecular catalysts immobilized to microsystem surfaces so
that catalyst activity is controlled by physical forces generated by the microsystem. Additionally, the program seeks high-accuracy
modeling and simulation of such integrated molecular microsystems. Through these demonstrations, MICA aims to answer three
critical questions: (1) how can microsystems be used to actively control molecules? (2) what are the different microsystem physics
that can be used to drive catalyst function? and (3) what co-design approaches can be used to integrate the different physics of
microsystems and molecules?

Beginning in FY 2026, this program will be funded in PE 0602025E, Project MSL-03.


