B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                  FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027
Title: Fast Event-based Neuromorphic Camera and Electronics (FENCE)                                                                      6.000          -             -
Description: The Fast Event-based Neuromorphic Camera and Electronics (FENCE) program developed and demonstrated a
low latency, low power event-based infrared (IR) camera to enable intelligent sensors for tactical DoW applications. Event-based
imagers are an emerging class of sensors with major demonstrated advantages relative to traditional cameras. State-of-the-art
visible event-based cameras have been shown to produce over two orders of magnitude less data in optimal conditions relative
to traditional framing cameras because they transmit data only from pixels that have changed. This leads directly to two orders of
magnitude lower data latency and a commensurate reduction in power consumption. Despite their inherent advantages, existing
event-based cameras were not compatible with DoW applications because DoW applications regularly face conditions that are
not optimal, where issues such as clutter and noise cause a large percentage of the event-based pixels to change simultaneously.
When this happens, such cameras did not perform significantly better than traditional cameras. FENCE developed an infrared
event-based imager, consistent with military requirements, that intelligently removes noise and clutter to maintain low power and
latency operation, even when faced with all of the pixels firing simultaneously. This new class of sensors enabled by FENCE are
capable of responding to fast moving targets and discriminating dim targets in noisy conditions.

Title: Generating RF with Photonics for low Noise (GRYPHON)                                                                              5.000             -            -
Description: The Generating RF with Photonics for low Noise (GRYPHON) program developed compact sources of microwaves
and millimeter waves with extremely low phase noise. Legacy compact signal sources, such as crystal oscillators, are too noisy to
support advanced military radar and communications functions. Conversely, best-in-class oscillators which use optical techniques
to synthesize extremely pure microwaves faced size and cost issues that inhibited deployment on the airborne systems,
munitions, and other size-constrained platforms where the DoW requires high-performance capabilities. The GRYPHON program
drew on recent advances in miniature optical components to replicate best-in-class optical frequency synthesis techniques in
microchip form factors.

Title: Quantum Imaging of Vector Electromagnetic Radiation (QuIVER)                                                                      2.000             -            -
Description: The Quantum Imaging of Vector Electromagnetic Radiation (QuIVER) program developed full-tensor magnetic
field sensors and demonstrated them in DoW-relevant applications and concept of operations. In addition to being diagnostically
relevant, such sensitive magnetometers could enable future human-machine/brain-machine interfaces. The DoW and industry
also use magnetometers to detect anomalies such as mineral/oil deposits, old wellheads, or of improvised explosive devices. In
addition, magnetometers offer the possibility of magnetic navigation, which may operate in GPS-denied environments.

