Title: Resilient Supply-and-Demand Networks (RSDN)                                                                                           -        4.060          4.060
Description: The Resilient Supply-and-Demand Networks (RSDN) program is developing supply-chain risk management
analytics to detect systemic challenges and improve resilience in supply and demand networks (SDN). At present, the separation
of supply-chain information into confidential silos obscures a system-wide view, inhibiting comprehensive risk-focused analysis of
supply and demand networks. RSDN is developing techniques for modeling and stress-testing real-world SDNs, including network
analytics and visualizations, to reveal emerging fragilities and enable deep situational awareness of systemic risks and potential
disruptions. An RSDN stress-testing framework enables repeatable scenario analysis of strategic issues in supply and demand
networks, automated analysis and discovery of risk patterns, and evaluation of alternative risk mitigation strategies.

Prior to FY 2026, this program was funded in PE 0602702E, Project TT-13.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Optimize forward and backward stress-testing capabilities for high priority use cases.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Collaborate with Department of War stakeholders to transition technologies to critical supply and demand network domains.
Title: FLexible networking Using Intelligent Dialecting (FLUID)                                                                              -       13.096          2.000
Description: FLexible networking Using Intelligent Dialecting (FLUID) will enable Command, Control, Computing,
Communications, Cyber, Intelligence, Surveillance, Reconnaissance, and Targeting (C5ISRT) under extremely constrained
internet protocol (IP) network environments, including those with link capacities in the range from 10s to single digit Kilobits per
second. FLUID will research technologies that reduce network and user communications with semantically correct but condensed
data, application, and/or protocol information. FLUID will apply intelligent mechanisms to reduce the link capacity required for
C5ISRT systems to operate at target scale. Research will focus on extracting and communicating compressed but semantically
similar bits from user data, application messages, and network protocol messages to fit within the network capacity constraints;
thus, creating the potential for greatly increased efficiency at and across the tactical edge. Software developed under the program
will transition to the Services.

Prior to FY 2026, this program was funded in PE 0603766E, Project NET-01.


