Title: Advanced Systems Studies and Concepts                                                                                                -       80.391        178.725
Description: Studies conducted under this program will explore emerging technologies, prototypes, and system concepts for
applicability to military use. This includes the degree and scope of potential impact and improvements to military operations,
mission utility, and warfighter capability. Research will also foster innovative system solutions and architectures at all levels
of military operations and enable tight coupling of platforms across land, air, sea, and space domains. Desired effects include
reducing potential adversaries' labor advantage by leveraging automation, modeling, and simulation technologies in support of
system design and development. Topics include reshaping design tools and processes enabled by automation to actively manage
engineering uncertainty, accelerated fixture development enabled by physics-informed modeling, and accelerated verification
analytics for decisions-making, authoring, testing and certification enabled by state-of-the-art machine automation. This program
also includes funding for potential classified program initiations.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Develop new methods of design space exploration that redefine system architectures, provide new insights into higher order
interactions, and enable tailored testing.
- Initiate research that enables seamless cross-domain communications into, within, and out of contested environments.
- Initiate research into a program to demonstrate a semi-autonomous platform that provides sensing, tracking, targeting, and
engagement capability.
- Develop platforms for sub-domain access to enable novel access and operational envelopes.
- Explore and refine advanced system concepts to deliver integrated, cross-domain platform autonomy at disruptive scale and
unprecedented penetration capabilities.
- Explore automated advanced sensing systems that leverage multi-modal computer vision and can be deployed on uncrewed
vehicles and with squad sized warfighting units.
- Explore concepts to provide a low-cost, easy-to-integrate, large-scale national infrastructure sensing system.
- Examine concepts and technology to prevent the impacts, degradation and disruption of port operations.
- Investigate rapid and ad hoc mechanisms for dynamic, composable, and adaptable uncrewed swarm systems.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Initiate research approaches to acquiring new defense systems, including disrupting systems engineering and reimaging test
and certification.
- Develop new design approaches to make manufacturable designs or to dramatically reduce human engineering effort.
- Develop new approaches to fabrication that enable rapid start-up, reduced production lead times, and frequent changes to
military systems.

