FY 2026 Plans:
- Explore AI technology for stack security.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Use formal analysis to prove the fidelity of scanned electronic devices.
- Develop scalable software analysis, sandboxing, and surveillance techniques to secure software development.
- Mitigate vulnerabilities to secure Department of War infrastructure.
- Use models of emergent communications as the basis for networks with strong privacy guarantees.
- Develop techniques for rapid reconstitution following any large-scale internet disruption/outage.
- Develop rigorous engineering approaches for assuring the use of foundation models in safety-critical systems.
- Develop physics-informed multimodal foundation models to enable rapid generation of highly accurate digital twins.
- Develop methods and tools to provide real-time ephemeral tactical data protection.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
The FY 2027 increase reflects studies and concepts initiations including, but not limited to, the advancement of new technologies
to support secure software development through scalable software analysis, sandboxing, and surveillance techniques, to
enable rapid reconstitution following any large-scale internet disruption/outage and to support development of physics-informed
multimodal foundation models to enable rapid generation of highly accurate digital twins.
Title: Advanced Cyber Operations Studies and Concepts                                                                                            -        4.875         14.825
Description: Efforts conducted under this thrust study, refine, prototype, demonstrate, and evaluate technologies to achieve
decisive and enduring operational advantages in the cyber domain. The thrust has two focus areas: Offensive Cyberspace
Operations (OCO) that aim to project power and deliver effects through actions in the cyber domain and Defensive Cyberspace
Operations (DCO) that aim to defend U.S. cyberspace. OCO interests span strategic, which includes attacks on adversary military
infrastructure, to tactical, which includes attacks on adversary weapons, combat, and information systems. In addition to overt
denial/disruption/destruction of adversary systems, OCO offers the potential for action that can undermine adversary confidence in
their systems and thereby deter adversary aggression. DCO focuses on defeating adversary malicious cyber activity by preventing
adversary access to U.S. networks and systems and by promptly discovering and remediating any compromise of U.S. systems.
For both OCO and DCO, prototypes are created to explore new cyber operations concepts and the evaluation and refinement of
these concepts is performed in collaboration with cyber operators. This thrust creates the new concepts and prototypes required
for the U.S. to achieve and maintain superior cyber warfighting capabilities. This effort also includes funding for potential classified
program initiations.

