Title: Autonomy Standards and Ideals with Military Operational Values (ASIMOV)                                                           22.789             -            -
Description: The Autonomy Standards and Ideals with Military Operational Values (ASIMOV) program developed an initial
autonomy benchmarking framework to objectively and quantitatively measure the readiness of future autonomous systems and
the operational complexity and difficulty of proposed use-cases in support of Military Operational Values (MOV) (e.g., international
humanitarian law, rules of engagement, commander's intent, etc.) in increasingly complex and changing scenarios. In order
to accelerate the development and eventual use of autonomous systems, an implementable measurement and benchmarking
framework of military autonomy must be developed. ASIMOV's benchmark will enable future autonomous systems that undergo
intensive testing to be evaluated and scored with autonomy readiness levels (ARL) much like how technology readiness levels
(TRL) and manufacturing readiness levels (MRL) are used to describe the maturity of technology and manufacturing processes,
respectively. ASIMOV decomposed the five U.S. Responsible Artificial Intelligence (AI) Principles (Responsibility, Equitability,
Reliability, Traceability, and Governability) and other MOVs in a structured, observable, and independently verifiable manner to
measure the readiness of specific autonomous systems to perform within complex and dynamic scenarios. Technology developed
under ASIMOV will support future autonomous systems research and development.

Title: FLexible networking Using Intelligent Dialecting (FLUID)                                                                          11.238             -            -
Description: FLexible networking Using Intelligent Dialecting (FLUID) will enable Command, Control, Computing,
Communications, Cyber, Intelligence, Surveillance, Reconnaissance, and Targeting (C5ISRT) under extremely constrained
internet protocol (IP) network environments, including those with link capacities in the range from 10s to single digit Kilobits per
second. FLUID will research technologies that reduce network and user communications with semantically correct but condensed
data, application, and/or protocol information. FLUID will apply intelligent mechanisms to reduce the link capacity required for
C5ISRT systems to operate at target scale. Research will focus on extracting and communicating compressed but semantically
similar bits from user data, application messages, and network protocol messages to fit within the network capacity constraints;
thus, creating the potential for greatly increased efficiency at and across the tactical edge. Software developed under the program
will transition to the Services.

Beginning in FY 2026, this program will be funded in PE 0603467E, Project DAT-01.

